Hermione jumped and clutched Harry’s arm.
“It’s okay,” said Harry reassuringly, and he led the way into the sitting room.
Bathilda was tottering around the place lighting candle, but it was still very
dark, not to mention extremely dirty. Thick dust crunched beneath their feet,
and Harry’s nose detected, underneath the dank and mildewed smell, something worse, like meat gone bad. He wondered when was the last time anyone
had been inside Bathilda’s house to check whether she was coping. She seemed
to have forgotten that she could do magic too, for she lit the candles clumsily
by hand, her trailing lace cuff in constant danger of catching fire.
