frames.
He wondered whether Bathilda or somebody else had removed them. Then
the sight of a photograph near the back of the collection caught his eye, and he
snatched it up.
It was the golden-haired, merry-faced thief, the young man who had perched
on Gregorovitch’s windowsill, smiling lazily up at Harry out of the silver frame.
And it came to Harry instantly where he had seen the boy before: in The Life
and Lies of Albus Dumbledore, arm in arm with teenage Dumbledore, and that
must be where all the missing photographs were in Rita’s book.
